node.title: Volunteer Dies After a Sheep Charges at Her on a Therapy Farm
node.description: Kim Taylor, 73, went into cardiac arrest after being attacked while caring for livestock at a Massachusetts farm, the police said.

node.title: Pence's Former Top Aide, Once Banned From the White House, Cooperating With Jan. 6 Committee
node.description: Pence's former chief of staff Marc Short, who was with Pence as he fled while insurrectionists were invading the Capitol, will speak to the House panel.

node.title: Nurse accused of faking teenager's COVID vaccination has fraud charge dropped
node.description: Police drop a fraud charge against a Perth nurse who was accused of falsely recording that a teenager had been given a COVID-19 vaccine, when the jab was never administered.

node.title: Home detention for selling livestock that didn't exist
node.description: While working for Rural Livestock Limited, John Francis Williams defrauded his employer as well as his clients by submitting false sale notes related to livestock sales and leasing agreements.

node.title: Covid-19: Hut in Fiordland National Park identified as a high-risk exposure site
node.description: A Department of Conservation hut in Fiordland National Park has been identified as a high-risk Covid-19 exposure site.

node.title: 1/6 Rioter Who Said She'd Avoid Jail Because She's 'White' Now Plans to 'Detox' in Prison
node.description: She listed yoga and working out as two of the activities she hoped to do while behind bars.

node.title: Man Arrested in 2018 for 1987 Cold Case Has Conviction Overturned Because of Juror Bias
node.description: The juror had experience of violence against a woman and didn't know if she, as a mother, could remain unbiased during the trial, she said.

node.title: Endangered right whale gives birth while entangled in ropes
node.description: An endangered North Atlantic right whale caught in a rope since March gives birth to a calf of the US south-eastern coastline.

node.title: Parents hope inquest into killing of Hannah Clarke and her children will 'fill in a few missing pieces'
node.description: A pre-inquest conference in Brisbane is told the evidence relating to the brutal murder of Hannah Clarke and her children "will paint a complex picture". A two-week inquest hearing has been set down for March.

node.title: Majority of staff unsatisfied with managers' competence - survey
node.description: New Zealand managers are falling short of expectations, with most workers giving high marks to their social interaction with colleagues and a failing grade to their managers.

node.title: Cryptocurrency providers at high risk of financial crime - FMA
node.description: The Financial Markets Authority has found that cryptocurrency service providers face a high risk of being targeted by money launderers and terrorism financiers.

node.title: Man Charged With Sending Dozens of Violent Threats to L.G.B.T.Q. Groups
node.description: Robert Fehring warned that an attack on New York City’s Pride March would make the Pulse nightclub shooting “look like a cakewalk,” the authorities said.

node.title: Defendant in Case Brought by Durham Says New Evidence Undercuts Charge
node.description: Lawyers for Michael Sussmann, accused by the Trump-era special counsel of lying to the F.B.I., asked for a quick trial after receiving what they said was helpful material from prosecutors.

node.title: Michael Steinhardt, Billionaire, Surrenders $70 Million in Stolen Relics
node.description: The hedge fund pioneer is barred for life from buying more antiquities. He turned over 180 stolen objects that had decorated his homes and office.

node.title: Flyer Charged in Jump to Tarmac; Family Says He Thought Someone Was Trying to Kill Him
node.description: "He was paranoid saying someone's going to get me," suspect Daniel Ramirez's sister-in-law said. "Someone's going to kill me."

node.title: Prosecutors Charge Man They Say Shot Jacqueline Avant, Security Guard and His Own Foot
node.description: Aariel Maynor, 29, who was previously convicted of assault, robbery, and grand theft, was on parole during the time of the shooting.

node.title: NT records no new local COVID cases, Katherine and surrounding communities likely to exit lockout tomorrow
node.description: The Northern Territory has not recorded any new local cases of COVID-19 in the past 24 hours, with lockout restrictions in Katherine and surrounding communities likely to be lifted tomorrow as scheduled.

node.title: Serial conman Peter Foster arrested after dodging Sydney court hearing six months earlier
node.description: Australian Federal Police officers arrest serial conman Peter Foster in Victoria, six months after he failed to appear before a Sydney court on fraud charges.

node.title: Fonterra lifts payout forecast to record high
node.description: The dairy giant has has raised its forecast milk payout to farmers to a record level $8.40 and $9 per kilogram of milk solids.

node.title: Sky cuts costs as sport and entertainment rights rise in price
node.description: The pay television operator Sky has lifted its profit guidance after cutting operating and capital costs, while improving revenue.

node.title: Crown under fire on Māori inclusion in Covid-19 response
node.description: Today was the first day of a special hearing into whether the Crown has breached Te Tiriti in its Covid-19 response.

node.title: Covid-19 update: 98 new community cases in NZ today
node.description: There are 74 new cases in Auckland today, 10 in Waikato, eight in Bay of Plenty, one in Taranaki and five in Nelson Marlborough.

node.title: Kāpiti Coast flooding: About 350 properties cut off after heavy rain
node.description: A small beachside community on the Kāpiti Coast is cut off due to overnight flooding. Audio

node.title: Navy suspends use of military tank farm above Hawaii aquifier
node.description: Nearly 1,000 military households have complained that their tap water smells like fuel. Some have complained that they have suffered cramps and vomiting.

node.title: Biden’s Supreme Court Commission Prepares to Vote on Final Report
node.description: A draft version of the document flagged deep disputes over court expansion while exploring how phasing in term limits might work.

node.title: ‘Selling Kabul’ Review: Trapped in a War, and an Apartment
node.description: In Sylvia Khoury’s suspenseful new play, the characters sometimes feel too much like wheels in a machine, but it’s a tense thrill to watch it work.

node.title: Syria Accuses Israel of Attack as Assad's Top Diplomat Joins Senior UAE Official in Iran
node.description: Iranian President Ebrahim Raisi called for deeper relations with both Syria and the UAE, which have intensified contacts as Damascus eyes an Arab League return.

node.title: Cops Kill Man Pulled Over in Ditch After He Ignores Commands, Allegedly Shoots Dog in Car
node.description: Troopers Joselo Mechuca and Eduardo Tejada responded to a report of a car that drove into a ditch in Knowlton Township, NJ, the attorney general's office said.

node.title: Kevin Rudd's apology to Indigenous peoples officially becomes a Sound of Australia
node.description: Kevin Rudd's Apology to Australia's Indigenous peoples and Gotye's Somebody That I Used to Know are among 10 new recordings inducted into the National Film and Sound Archive's Sounds of Australia for 2021.

node.title: Vital radar switched on in Queensland outback just in time for La Niña wet season
node.description: One night in 2019, graziers in a vast radar blackspot thought they were set to get 60mm of rain. They ended up with flooding that caused $5.68b worth of damage. But now, just in time for summer, a crucial new radar system is operating.
